{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538105"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:24:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:24:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16138"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16138"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.05,0.28,0.04,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8829"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115984"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8829"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16138"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97983"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1315"},{"type":"tags","id":"1571"},{"type":"tags","id":"4721"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21060"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35461"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35462"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43611"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49573"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115984"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic requesting information about natural family planning methods (fertility awareness method). She has regular 28-day menstrual cycles and does not want to use hormonal or barrier contraception for personal reasons. She is aware that the method is not 100% effective and is willing to risk a potential unplanned pregnancy but would ideally like to delay pregnancy at this time. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is in a monogamous relationship and has recently had a negative sexually transmitted infection screen. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice regarding the fertility awareness method?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Basal body temperature will rise after ovulation","Tracking cervical mucus changes alone will be effective","Avoid intercourse for three days before ovulation","Take oral temperature measurements at different times each day","Resume unprotected intercourse for 10 days after menstruation begins"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen counselling patients about contraceptive options, it is essential to provide accurate information about effectiveness. The fertility awareness method requires careful tracking of multiple physiological markers to identify fertile days in the menstrual cycle and avoiding sex during the fertile time. The most effective method is a combination of monitoring cervical mucus changes, basal body temperature and tracking the timing of menstrual cycles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasal body temperature will rise after ovulation\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. There is a small but detectable rise of 0.2-0.5\u00b0C in basal body temperature after ovulation due to progesterone\u0027s thermogenic effect. This temperature rise helps confirm that ovulation has occurred but cannot predict when ovulation will occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETracking cervical mucus changes alone\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient. Effective use of fertility awareness requires monitoring multiple signs including basal body temperature, cervical mucus changes and calendar tracking of the menstrual cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAvoid intercourse for three days before ovulation\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate advice. The fertile window extends from about five days before ovulation through to one day after ovulation, as sperm can survive in the female reproductive tract for up to five days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETake oral temperature measurements at different times each day\u003C/strong\u003E would give inaccurate readings. Basal body temperature must be measured at the same time each morning before any activity, as even small variations in timing can affect the reading.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResume unprotected intercourse for 10 days after menstruation begins\u003C/strong\u003E could result in pregnancy. For a patient with a typical 28-day cycle, ovulation is likely to occur on day 14, and sperm survival means the fertile window may overlap with unprotected intercourse. Ovulation can occur at variable times in the cycle, which is why it is recommended that patients use more than just the calendar-based method of fertility tracking when using the fertility awareness method.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen discussing fertility awareness methods, it is important to emphasise that more reliable contraceptive options are available, including long-acting reversible contraception with failure rates less than 1%. However, if a patient chooses this method, they should be educated about all components and the importance of consistent use. While fertility awareness methods can be very effective in the longer term or if it is done correctly, typical failure in the first year is up to 25% due to the complexity of the monitoring required. It is also complicated by anxiety, travel or weight gain which can affect the menstrual cycle, and only suitable for patients who have regular periods and can adhere to strict avoidance of sex during the fertile time.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The fertility awareness method has a typical-use failure rate of up to 25% in the first year of use.","Fertility awareness requires tracking of multiple physiological markers including cervical mucus, basal body temperature, and menstrual cycle.","Patient education about fertility awareness methods should include discussion of more reliable contraceptive options."],"references":["Family Planning NSW. Fertility awareness based methods of contraception, lactational amenorrhoea and withdrawal [Internet]. Sydney: Family Planning NSW. Available at: https://www.fpnsw.org.au/health-information/contraception/fertility-awareness-based-methods-contraception-lactational","Mazza D, Hampton K. Fertility-awareness knowledge, attitudes and practices of women attending general practice. Aust Fam Physician. 2015 Nov;44(11):840\u20135. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2015/november/fertility-awareness-knowledge-attitudes-and-practi"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97983"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16138"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97983"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-26T21:40:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-26T21:41:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8829"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115984"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group"